Your main problem is that YAML [does not have a MIME type][1]. Even if it did, MIME type detection is typically done using what&#39;s called a [magic number][2]. Since YAML isn&#39;t required to have [any kind of identifier][3], it would be difficult to use that sort of detection and you&#39;d probably get unreliable results.

Using [the finfo class][4] you should be able to determine if a file is XML. So, your best bet is to check the file using `finfo::file()` and if it comes back as text/plain, try using your Yaml parser and see if it works.


    $finfo = new \finfo(FILEINFO_MIME_TYPE);
    $test = $finfo-&gt;file($path);
    if ($test === &quot;text/xml&quot;) {
        // parse as XML
    } else {
        // parse as YAML
    }

  [1]: https://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml
  [2]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_format#Magic_number
  [3]: https://yaml.org/spec/1.2/spec.html#id2781553
  [4]: https://www.php.net/finfo

