I would recommend using `std::vector` instead. For instance this here:

```
int main() {
	std::vector&lt;Vec&gt; u(5, 3);
}
```

Makes a vector of `5` `Vec` with `3` `Complex` each. However, the constructor is only called once and then it&#39;s copied five times, so you need to implement a copy constructor, otherwise they would all share one instance of `vect`:

```
Vec(const Vec&amp; other){
		std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;copied size &quot; &lt;&lt; other.dim &lt;&lt; std::endl;
		dim = other.dim;
		vect = new int[dim];
		for (int i = 0; i &lt; dim; i++)
			vect[i] = other.vect[i];
	}
```

And in order to not have a memory leak, you also need a destructor:

```
~Vec() {
	delete[] vect;
	std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;deleted &quot; &lt;&lt; dim &lt;&lt; std::endl;
}
```

Both are not the same case, in the first you know the size of the vector at compiling time. Better try to use the std::vector, in this way you don&#39;t need to worry about memory administration.


    class Vec
    {
    private:
        int dim;
        std::vector&lt;Complex&gt; vect;
    public:
        Vec(int n):dim(n){
            vect.resize(dim);
        }
    };

